### Interfaces in Dart

Every class in Dart implicitly defines an interface. You can implement one or more interfaces using the `implements` keyword.

```dart
class Flyable {
  void fly() => print('Flying');
}

class Swimmable {
  void swim() => print('Swimming');
}

class Duck implements Flyable, Swimmable {
  @override
  void fly() => print('Duck flying');

  @override
  void swim() => print('Duck swimming');
}

void main() {
  var duck = Duck();
  duck.fly();
  duck.swim();
}
```

### implements vs extends

| Aspect | extends | implements |
|--------|---------|------------|
| Relationship | IS-A | CAN-DO |
| Code reuse | Inherits implementation | No code reuse |
| Multiple | Single parent | Multiple interfaces |
| Method bodies | Inherited | Must override all |

### Using Interface Classes

```dart
// Defining an interface class
interface class Drawable {
  void draw() => print('Drawing');
}

class Circle implements Drawable {
  @override
  void draw() => print('Drawing a circle');
}

// interface class can only be implemented, not extended
// class Ellipse extends Drawable {} // ERROR if in different library
```

### Multiple Interface Implementation

```dart
abstract class Logger {
  void log(String message);
}

abstract class Database {
  void save(String data);
}

class FileLoggerAndDB implements Logger, Database {
  @override
  void log(String message) => print('LOG: $message');

  @override
  void save(String data) => print('Saved: $data');
}
```

### Interface Conventions

```dart
// Common convention: define abstract class as interface
abstract class Cache {
  void put(String key, dynamic value);
  dynamic get(String key);
  void clear();
}

class MemoryCache implements Cache {
  final _store = <String, dynamic>{};

  @override
  void put(String key, dynamic value) => _store[key] = value;

  @override
  dynamic get(String key) => _store[key];

  @override
  void clear() => _store.clear();
}
```

> **Key Point:** Dart does not have a separate `interface` keyword (though `interface class` exists for restrictions). Every class can be used as an interface with `implements`. Use `implements` when you want to promise behavior without inheriting implementation.

codeExample:
interface class JsonSerializable {
  Map<String, dynamic> toJson() => {};
}

interface class Validatable {
  bool validate() => true;
}

class User implements JsonSerializable, Validatable {
  String name;
  int age;

  User(this.name, this.age);

  @override
  Map<String, dynamic> toJson() => {'name': name, 'age': age};

  @override
  bool validate() => name.isNotEmpty && age > 0;
}

void main() {
  var user = User('Alice', 30);
  print(user.toJson());
  print('Valid: ${user.validate()}');
}
